<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Used Car</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I am relatively new to pulling a dungeon with a shaman, but not new at all to pulling in general.  My old main was a monk and I had also root parked (stun then root) when I would play my cleric as well.<br />
When Ldon came out I would generally have a guild cleric pull with pacify, even with a monk present, simply because in ldon, FD is way too slow a method.<br />
  <br />
Then came the times in which we had neither a monk nor a cleric with the 65 pacify and even times with a bard who could not pull very well, so I decided what the hell.  <br />
Some of the areas looked simple enough to pull via root or slow, so I started doing it for almost every group I made, unless I had a reliable bard (which I prefer).  <br />
I always have tigirs up for A)big add pulls and B) it pulls most of the mobs off the rest of the group so I can park them.<br />
And when I nuke, it is generally Saryrns Tears when a mob is at 50% and then I run off for more, while it rains down.  It really lets me do something active for the party and keeps the dps where it should be.<br />
<br />
Also thought it would be good to add that if you are having problems pulling mobs away from the party due to various reasons (people not assisting or healer agro), simply back away and sit down after slowing.  If the mob was not taunted or there was not some huge quick heal just performed, it should rush right for you.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=600034&amp;resize" target="_blank">Spare Parts</a></div>
	
	
